<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-676-984  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 676 984.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Sept 18 1989 v6 n37 p32(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Making the 'new' factory. (Industry Focus: Manufacturing feature)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Chartoff, Marvin; Cordovano, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Integrated information networks will be crucial components of theautomated factory environment of the future.andP;  The manufacturingsystems that support automation divide into three categories.andO;Engineering automation includes hardware and software such ascomputer-aided design and manufacturing (CAD/CAM) andcomputer-aided engineering (CAE) simulation systems.andO;Manufacturing automation includes programmable controls, roboticsand drive systems.andP;  Information management tools control factoryoperations and provide an integrated platform for integrating datafrom the engineering and manufacturing environments.andP;  Integrationremains the key to successful long-range planning for advancedmanufacturing system concepts.andP;  Planners need to document currentflow procedures, processes, systems and networks and develop thenetwork architecture that will support the automated system model.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationTechnologyCAD-CAMFactory ManagementGoals and Objectives.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Manufacturing systems that support information management. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>